postcontent:
This Kit Includes:
- 3~9x42MM VARIABLE POWER MINI-SCOPE -
-  RUGER 10/22 PICATINNY RAIL SCOPE MOUNT -

$85.00 Includes Free Shipping

= = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = =

The Ruger 10/22 is one of the most popular 22 rifles in the world and many types of scopes and mounts are available for this handy little carbine. Many of the compact and mini-scopes being manufactured today rival the performance of full size scopes while offering lighter weight and smaller profiles. These features make them ideal for rim fire and other small caliber sporting rifles and, even though the eye relief on these mini-scopes equals that of the full size scopes, they do present a problem. Because of their short length, they need to be mounted further back on the receiver.

Most Weaver style scope mounts were made to accommodate full size scopes on high power rifles and don’t work well on smaller 22s. Until recently, there were few mounts made that could effectively accommodate the smaller mini-scopes while still maintaining proper eye relief.

We have a unique, reversible Picatinny rail scope mount for the Ruger 10/22 rim fire rifle that can be installed in two positions. In the forward position it accommodates the longer full size scopes, but when the mount is reversed, a mini-scope can be mounted further back to obtain a full field of view.

We installed this Picatinny rail mount on several of our Ruger 10/22s and mounted a variety of fixed and variable power mini-scopes using different types and brands of scope rings. The result of these experiments were several Ruger 10/22 packages, including this kit, which offer great values for hunters and target shooters.

Leave the power set on 3x or 4x in the field and you’re ready for close-in fast moving targets. As the target range increases, turn the magnification ring up to a higher power and you are ready for longer shots. For those really long shots at smaller targets, steady the rifle on a solid rest and turn the power ring up to the full 9X power.

The mil-dot reticle can be used to estimate the range to your target and the smaller scope profile makes it easier to carry your Ruger 10/22 in the field or fit it into a scabbard or gun case.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1996 ws6 T/A
postcontent: I have installed a new battery, cleaned the spark splugs, checked spark, checked the starter, and am able to crank the motor without issues, I have determined that it needs a fuel pump and will not start at this time, however the engine is mechanically sound and builds nearly 40 psi of oil pressure during cranking. I also have fresh oil, oil filter, coolant and spark plug wires that I will give you with the car. This WS6 T/A has numerous upgrades, and several thousand dollars invested in both the engine and rear end. It has not run since Feb 2009, since I put it in storage just before I joined the Army. It should need nothing more than any other vehicle that has sat for a while; some TLC. I built the short block while I was attending UTI automotive school in Southern California, its an LT1 Gen 2 SBC V-8, currently at 355 cubic inches, in front of a T-56 6 speed manual, it has a forged Eagle crank, forged Eagle I-beam rods, forged Speed Pro flat top pistons, a custom cam that I had reground from a Comp Cams camshaft, the specs on the custom grind are 233/233 @ .050 .542/.542 valve lift with 1.6 rockers, ground on a 112 degree LSA, it has Proform 1.6 anodized aluminum full roller rockers, Comp Cams double valve springs, stock heads, intake manifold and exhaust manifolds. The engine also has other small mods, such as some modifications I made to the factory ram air box like a K&N filter, home made smooth bellow, an LT4 knock sensor to work properly with the roller rockers, PCM tune, Ford Racing(I got an amazing deal I couldnt pass up, even if they say Ford lol) 42 LB/hr EV6 injectors w/ harnesses to work with the factory EV1 harness, and other little things not worth listing. The rear end has forged Tom's Gears 3.73 ring and pinion, with forged Tom's Gears 28 spline axles, and ARP wheel studs that I shortened to make the car look stock from the outside, sitting on Mickey Thompson E/T street radials in the rear, measuring 275/40/R17. The exhaust system has both cats gutted, running to a single Spintech Street Series 3" muffler, which runs to the drivers side exhaust tip, the passenger side is there but only to keep the stock look, and the single 3" exhaust helps to build low RPM torque, since the somewhat aggressive camshaft's powerband is approx 3000-7000+ RPM. Again, there are other small mods, but not worth listing, I built this vehicle by myself, and it was stock when I bought it, so everything done to it has been by my hands, and none of what I have listed is fake, false, an exaggeration, or a guess. I also have other parts for it that I'm willing to let go for a fair price, namely a Ram HD series clutch kit, which it will need anyways, and a set of Hooker Headers, which it could really use, if you are interested in the parts let me know.

title: For Sale:  FN Scar-L AEG, Echo 1 Stag Arms M4 AEG (custom), LPAEG M4, and airsoft equipment package.
postcontent:
I'm selling my FN Scar-L which I bought for $410 off of Airsplat, my Echo 1 Stag Arms custom made M4 which is a $200+ value, an LPAEG M4, My tactical vest (ACU), a size L ACU uniform, and 2 sets of high quality goggles. ALL SOLD TOGETHER FOR $400!!!(negotiable) I just need to make room in my closet and gun cabinet for new things. This deal I basically a steal for you so please Text me at REDACTED for any questions, more pictures, or if you're interested. 

The FN Scar-L was bought in May of 2010 and I've taken good care of it. I clean this, and all of my guns after every use and I even upgraded the gearbox to a high frequency pressure motor so it shoots a lot harder and more accurately. It shoots at roughly 430~450 fps.
The Echo 1 M4 was bought in July of 2012. This gun is my masterpiece. The only thing that's stock on this gun is the base frame that has the trademarks on it. Everything else is improved and upgraded. It has a brand new G&G gearbox, a 6.01mm 230mm tight bore barrel, a stable fixed stock with a medium sized battery hole for no rattling, a 4 point floating RIS, everything is either stainless steel, aluminum, or a tough polymer plastic (stronger than ABS plastic), it comes with a red/green dot sight that's made from AimSports (69.99 value, used only once). This thing is a beast. I put about $300 into it which is the cost of the gun and all the upgrades. It also comes with a high capacity 600rd extended magazine. It shoots at a steady 435 fps with .25g bb's and it shoots pretty fast and accurately for only having an 8.4v 1500mAh battery. If you upgrade the battery, you'll have a monster at your disposal. 
The LPAEG M4 is nothing too special at all. It was my first gun and its kinda dinged up because its just basic plastic. It shoots well though. It shoots at a steady 353 with .2g bb's but .12 is preferred with it. also, I'm willing to give away 15,000 .12g bb's with this gun.
The tactical vest is ACU digital camouflage. it has many pockets and pouches. there's 4 M4 mag pouches, 6 pistol mag pouches, 3 of which can be used for most sub machine gun magazines, a random accessories pouch, and shotgun shell holders. Its a one size fits most vest and I assure you that it will fit.
The uniform is standard issue military ACU digital camouflage. I only wore it twice. Its a large and I fit in a medium. although it is a large, it did fit me okay but I want one that fits me pretty well. 
The goggles are shatter proof and fog proof. They have complete eye protection and are very comfortable to wear. Doesn't matter if i bought it at walmart yesterday or have had it in my closet ten years ago. It's selling more than retail nationwide right now, not just in Indy.  I am still looking for some ammo but I'm not going to pay a crazy price for it. I will wait and pray it comes back down but it may not. There's only one person to be mad at for making stupid purchasing decisions,and you know who that is!  What do all of you think is going to happen when we waiting for a truck to show up at wal-mart that has a little food on it instead of ammo when the dollar collapses. Hopefully you have preferred your friends and neighbors to help one another. Although I hope that day never comes, if it does, guess what the price of a bag of my rice and beans will cost you?
